package main

import (
	"context"
	"fmt"
	"os"

	metav1 "k8s.io/apimachinery/pkg/apis/meta/v1"
	"k8s.io/client-go/kubernetes"
	"k8s.io/client-go/tools/clientcmd"
	"k8s.io/client-go/util/retry"
)

func main() {
	// 1. Setup (Standard boilerplate)
	kubeconfig := os.Getenv("HOME") + "/.kube/config"
	config, _ := clientcmd.BuildConfigFromFlags("", kubeconfig)
	clientset, _ := kubernetes.NewForConfig(config)

	ctx := context.Background()
	namespace := "default"
	podName := "example-pod"

	// 2. Use retry.RetryOnConflict to handle Optimistic Concurrency
	// This function will re-run the closure if a 409 Conflict occurs.
	err := retry.RetryOnConflict(retry.DefaultRetry, func() error {
		// a) Always fetch the LATEST version of the object inside the retry loop
		pod, err := clientset.CoreV1().Pods(namespace).Get(ctx, podName, metav1.GetOptions{})
		if err != nil {
			return err
		}

		// b) Modify the Status (Note: This assumes the status subresource is enabled)
		pod.Status.Message = "Backup in progress"
		pod.Status.Reason = "AutomationUpdate"

		// c) Update the Status subresource
		_, updateErr := clientset.CoreV1().Pods(namespace).UpdateStatus(ctx, pod, metav1.UpdateOptions{})
		return updateErr
	})

	if err != nil {
		fmt.Printf("Update failed after retries: %v\n", err)
		os.Exit(1)
	}

	fmt.Println("Successfully updated Pod status with concurrency handling!")
}

/*
Technical Deep Dive for the Interview

1) Why UpdateStatus instead of Update?
In Kubernetes, Update modifies the full object (including Spec).
If a controller only reports observations, UpdateStatus is safer because it
avoids accidentally overwriting user-defined Spec fields.
It also enables tighter RBAC boundaries by granting status-only write access.

2) The resourceVersion Mechanism
Kubernetes uses an atomic compare-and-swap model.
If your local copy is resourceVersion 100 and etcd is already at 101, the write
is rejected with a conflict.
With retry.RetryOnConflict, you re-fetch version 101, re-apply business logic,
and submit again as a newer version (for example, 102).

3) Conditions vs. Phases
In enterprise platforms (for example CSI Storage and Longhorn integrations),
teams avoid relying on a single status string.
Instead they model Conditions, which include:
- Type (for example Ready)
- Status (True/False)
- LastTransitionTime
This gives a useful audit trail for why a resource is in its current state.

Summary of the "Golang for K8s" Toolkit
- Discovery and Cleanup: Find/delete resources based on metadata (time/status).
- Observation: Use Watch APIs to react to real-time changes.
- Reconciliation: Update state safely with optimistic concurrency + retries.

Final Prep Step
For Rancher (RKE) and CSI/Longhorn-focused roles, prepare examples for:
- A Custom Resource Definition (CRD) you would build a controller around.
- Terraform snippets used to provision and bootstrap an RKE cluster.
